div.div: Duet Debugging Notes:
Relvance of Debugging Modes To Print Job's Data-Acquisition:
* Platform (0) = No relevance - no text shown
* Network (1) = No relevance - shows # of received bytes)
* Webserver (2) = No relevance - shows http req and sending JSON reply
* Gcodes (3) = Relevant - shows which gcodes are inputted with request origins (e.g. file, serial)
* Move (4) = Relevant - detailed information on motor movement
* Heat (5) = No relevance - no text shown (even with manual temp changes)
* DDA (6) = No relevance - shows "recursion start #" (which is either 1,2, or 3)
* Roland (7) = No relevance - no text shown
* Scanner (8) = No relevance - no text shown
* PrintMonitor (9) = No relevance - no text shown

* use a for loop for the object retrieval (set the retrival time).

** house ALL operations involving prepping and sending m-codes to DWC in a single, separate file (e.g. send.js)
* Receiving operations are still housed in app.js

* Dynamically retrieve IP address or require manual input

div.div:
Sending Mcode/Gcodes To DWC:
* Not recommended to use Telnet communication, due to security reasons.
* Use axios.get function (with the rr_gcode?gcode=<insert gcode here> for both sending Mcodes and Gcodes
** Only proven for single line code execution (need verification for macros and multiple line gcode)
** Use "%" for spaces
* Can send gcode and mcodes during prints.

* use axios.get function (with the rr_status?type=<insert number here>) to get responses from different states
** type=3 is from active printing
** type=2 is ... not sure
** type=1 is ... not sure

div.div:
Mcodes/Gcodes to Optimize
* Tool Temp: G10 P0 S#
* Axis Steps: M92 X# Y# Z# E#
** M92 S# may be useful
* Extruder Temp: M104 S#
* Fan PWM: M106 P# S#
* Extruder Temp (Wait): M109 S# R# (this is for highly experimental recovery options)
* Bed Temp (Fast): M140 S#
* Chamber Temp (Fast): M141 S#
* Bed Temp (Wait): M190 S# R# (this is for highly experimental recovery options)
* Chamber Temp (Wait): M191 S# R# (this is for highly experimental recovery options)
* Max Accel: M201 X# Y# Z# E#
* Max Feedrate: M203 X# Y# Z# E#
* Max Print & Travel Accel: M204 P# T#
* Max Jerk: M205 X# Y# Z# E# (used as alternative to M566, Marlin compatible)
* Speed Factor Override %: M220 S#
* Extruder Factor Override %: M221 S# D#
* Extruder PID Parameters: M301 H# P# I# D# (this is for highly experimental optimization)
* Bed PID Parameters: M304 P# I# D# (this is for highly experimental optimization)
* Heating Process Parameters: M307 H# A# C# D# V# (this for highly experimental optimization)
* Microstepping: M350 (not sure if this is useful)
* Filament Wdith & Nozzle Diam. : M404 N# D# (only use for volumetric E values)
* Max Jerk: M566 X# Y# Z# E#
* Mixing Ratio: M568 E#
* Motor Driver Configuration: M570 (so many complicated variables, highly advanced optimization variable)
* Set output on extruder: M571 S# F# P# (this is an interesting control method, not sure how to use)
* Extruder Pressure Advance: M572 D# S#
* Nonlinear Extrusion: M592 D# A# B# L# T# (this is for highly experimental optimization)
* Motor Currents: M902 X# Y# Z# E#

Conceptual Definition of Case-study ML Aplication
* Using reinforced learning framework
* will use DQN (Deep Q Network) to use neural networks and estimate the Q value
** picked specifically to estimate q values knowing it will do so more unknown states
** assuming the action space is not large enough to effect convergence time (not using DDPG)
* using this link for RL with DQN foundation:
** https://towardsdatascience.com/introduction-to-various-reinforcement-learning-algorithms-i-q-learning-sarsa-dqn-ddpg-72a5e0cb6287
